                    </div>
                    <span>Once I picked up a book entitled 'Heroes of the Civil War' or something close to this. In it  was stated that it was a known fact that there were some 10,000 or more 'Medal of Honor' recipients in the northern army and not one medal issued to the cowardly secesh! Nowhere did it state that most of these medals were subsequently stipped from the recipients nor that the rebel army neither had the metal to make them nor a reason to award defenders of their hearth and homes. McPherson's Antietam doesn't reach this level of claptrap, but is of the same ilk with a 21st century twist in my view. 
<br />
<br />If you are looking for a detail of the battle or how the fog of war played out on this important battlefield, don't expect it here. The lucky Lee was found out, and the sympathetic McClellan beat him back with half a will. Wham, bam, it was over! 
<br />
<br />This book is 98% spin, the winners spin, of course. From a perspective of knowing how the war ended up, it is just a matter of seeing the inevitible. How could they have been so stupid back then? Any fool could see that the righteous north would pull this off. They had the high ground, right? The secesh were basically evil, no? 
<br />
<br />For my two cents (more than this book is worth) I wonder how many centuries must pass before most American scholars will arrive at a balanced view of this tragic chapter in our history. Based upon McPherson, a recognized expert, we have a couple more to go.  </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">An excellent study for novice and serious student alike.</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
