                      <span>3</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-19</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>CROSSROADS of FREEDOM: Antietam is an excellent study of ONE of the pivotal moments in American history.In "Hallowed Ground"...McPherson's even briefer essay on the battle of Gettysburg...GETTYSBURG is noted as "an event without equal...with the welfare of the republic itself"(p.18);and as what British historian Sir Edward Creasy regarded "the sixteenth decisive battle of the world"...
<br />
<br />The key thesis Professor McPherson proposes is that without the Union's Pyrrhic victory at Antietam(where Federal and Confederate Forces equally suffered casualties approximating 13,000 per Army)the American Civil War may have catastrophically concluded: and Government of,for and by the people perished from the earth FOUR SCORE & Six years from the founding of the Republic, with recognition of the Confederacy by Europe;subsequent"mediation" of Truce;and the end of the UNITED STATES. As other reviewers observe, there had been a tremendous and devastating reversal of Union Army fortune that had put The Army of the Potomac...once within 5 miles of Richmond...on the run and demoralized. A vainglorious General George B. McClellan is fascinating study in megalomania, near-criminal insubordination; and almost"feckless" timorousness. His personal feud with General Pope(and its  consequence for the Union cause)is nothing less than astonishing. McClellans's pettiness; inability to act when "handed" the battle[The Providential finding of Special Order 191 on September 12,1862 stating General Lee's command to divide his Army into four elements AGAINST WHICH ACTION ON THE PART OF MCCLELLAN(...in reversed circumstance,Lee or Jackson would certainly have boldly attempted...)could have destroyed The Army of Northern Virgina in detail, thus ending War];yet ironic and undeniable charisma among his troops which steeled them to fight and "win" the bloodiest single day(of)battle in American history is focal point of this study. Furthermore, it's indisputably demonstrated that President Lincoln was in battle not only with the Southern Confederacy; a vast number of Northern political enemies(particularly Democrats who adopted "the war is a failure" as their platform for 1862 Congressional Election..and which McClellan himself would adopt in opposing Lincoln in the Presidential Election of 1864)but many Officers within the Union General Staff(!).
<br />
<br />Professor McPherson's essay also stresses that victory at Antietam permitted President Lincoln to issue THE EMANCIPATION PROCLAMATION...freeing slaves in "Southern States in rebellion"[as only Constitutional Amendment could effect such a radical"understanding" and mutation of black men's rights (recall the Dred Scott Supreme Court Decision of 1857).] This overtly altered the NATURE OF THE CIVIL WAR itself...as many affected to understand and wage it...and foreshadowed A NEW BIRTH OF FREEDOM. 
<br />
<br />ANTIETAM...this pivotal moment in American and world history...is typically excellent writing of Professor McPherson. His ability to contextualize and provide comprehensive analysis of the battle and its implications goes beyond mere strategic/tactical military treatment. This is excellent study for novice or serious student going beyond the topically political/historical by providing a philosophical"telescope-in-reverse" describing Plays & Players, who...on September 17,1862...fought to(effectively)save or destroy the United States in a way no Enemy has truly attempted(though 9/11 may have been such an attack)or...with continued blessing of God,shall ever accomplish... 
<br />  </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Needs a different title</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
